            <!-- 3 Rules Section -->
            <section id="rules" class="section">
                <h2>The 3 Golden Rules of Exercise Prescription</h2>
                
                <div class="module-card">
                    <h3>🎯 Core Philosophy</h3>
                    <p style="font-size: 1.2em; line-height: 1.8; margin: 15px 0; font-style: italic;">
                        "Our ongoing clinical success is in the ability to guide our patients to participate in the most relevant 
                        physical activity for their current and future contexts."
                    </p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px;">These 3 rules apply to everyone from recreational athletes to elite performers, and from acute injuries to chronic conditions.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="info-box">
                    <h3>📚 Essential Exercise Science Nomenclature</h3>
                    <ul style="margin: 15px 0 0 20px; line-height: 1.8;">
                        <li><strong>Tempo:</strong> Speed at which movement is performed</li>
                        <li><strong>Time Under Tension (TUT):</strong> Reps × tempo</li>
                        <li><strong>Volume:</strong> Proxy for work in a session (sets × reps × load)</li>
                        <li><strong>Load:</strong> External (kg, %RM) or internal (RPE, VAS, HR, VO₂)</li>
                        <li><strong>SAID Principle:</strong> Specific Adaptations to Imposed Demands</li>
                        <li><strong>Progressive Overload:</strong> Increasing work to drive adaptation</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rule-grid">
                    <div class="rule-card">
                        <h3>Rule 1: Know Your Biological Factors Brutally Well</h3>
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px; font-size: 1.1em;">This is how you reason what the exercise is doing to the tissues</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="rule-card">
                        <h3>Rule 2: Know the Goals - Make Sure They Match!</h3>
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px; font-size: 1.1em;">Don't butcher the SAID principle. Match person AND task</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="rule-card">
                        <h3>Rule 3: Know Your Patient's Personal Preferences</h3>
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px; font-size: 1.1em;">Exercise only works if they actually DO it!</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="module-card">
                    <h3>Rule 1: Know Your Biological Factors Brutally Well</h3>
                    
                    <h4>🔧 A. Biomechanics</h4>
                    
                    <div style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 15px 0;">
                        <h4>Arthrokinematics / Kinetics</h4>
                        <p style="margin: 10px 0;">Your expert knowledge of modifying body positions to solve movement problems.</p>
                        
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Example Problem:</strong> Anterior knee pain at certain load in squat</p>
                        <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Solution:</strong> Sit back into hips to decrease external flexion moment on knee (within tissue capacity), transferring increased moment to hip</p>
                        
                        <div class="success-box" style="margin-top: 15px;">
                            <p><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Manipulate exercise selection / range of motion to adjust arthrokinematics</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 15px 0;">
                        <h4>Whole System Kinetics</h4>
                        <p style="margin: 10px 0;">Forces acting on the whole system - play with tempo, TUT, reps, and load to modify total system kinetics without changing the movement.</p>
                        
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Example:</strong> Same squat problem, different solution</p>
                        <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Solution:</strong> Don't change exercise - change HOW it's done to decrease total system GRF and impulse within knee joint capacity</p>
                        
                        <div class="success-box" style="margin-top: 15px;">
                            <p><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Think isometrics and heavy slow resistance for tendinopathy</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <p><strong>Summary:</strong> Change the way the movement LOOKS to deload a sensitive tissue, OR change the way the whole system is LOADED to deload a sensitive tissue.</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <h4 style="margin-top: 30px;">🧬 B. Biochemistry / Cellular Biology</h4>
                    
                    <p style="margin: 15px 0;">Pragmatic knowledge of cellular processes allows you to get the most bang for your buck and minimize disuse atrophy in rehab.</p>
                    
                    <div style="background: #e3f2fd; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 15px 0;">
                        <h4>The 3 Mechanisms of Mechanotransduction</h4>
                        
                        <h5 style="margin-top: 15px;">1️⃣ Mechanical Tension</h5>
                        <p style="margin: 10px 0;">Muscle cells detect stretch via special proteins → triggers muscle protein synthesis</p>
                        <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px;">
                            <li>More growth with full ROM vs. isometric for same volume</li>
                            <li><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Train through full ROM with higher external loads</li>
                        </ul>
                        
                        <h5 style="margin-top: 15px;">2️⃣ Muscle Damage</h5>
                        <p style="margin: 10px 0;">High volumes (especially eccentric) → tissue breakdown → satellite cell recruitment → more muscle tissue</p>
                        <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px;">
                            <li>Subsequent stress spread across more tissue</li>
                            <li><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Increase total volume load and eccentric load</li>
                        </ul>
                        
                        <h5 style="margin-top: 15px;">3️⃣ Metabolic Stress / Accumulation</h5>
                        <p style="margin: 10px 0;">High volume + reduced rest → metabolic by-products accumulate → chemoreceptors detect disruption → hormonal cascade → muscle protein synthesis</p>
                        <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px;">
                            <li>Think "the burn" from high rep or isometric exercises</li>
                            <li><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> Increase TUT, minimize rest, work at/above lactate threshold</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="warning-box">
                        <h4>⚠️ Critical Application: Post-Operative Rehab</h4>
                        <p style="margin: 10px 0;"><strong>Problem:</strong> Limited by GRF or shear/compression forces → can't apply much mechanical tension or create moderate muscle damage (low external load, decreased ROM, low training volumes)</p>
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Solution:</strong> Maximize metabolic stress to maintain anabolic stimulus:</p>
                        <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px;">
                            <li>Lower load</li>
                            <li>Decreased ROM</li>
                            <li>High TUT</li>
                            <li>Low inter-set recovery periods</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="success-box">
                        <p><strong>Summary:</strong> In most circumstances, patients can't use 1 or 2 of these mechanisms due to injury or pain. You better know how to maximize the one they CAN use to minimize effects of deloading!</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="module-card">
                    <h3>Rule 2: Know the Goals - Make Sure They Match!</h3>
                    
                    <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin: 15px 0;">Don't butcher the SAID principle.</p>
                    
                    <div style="background: #f5f5f5; padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 15px 0;">
                        <h4>Specificity Relates to the PERSON, Not Just the Tasks</h4>
                        <p style="margin: 10px 0;">Your analysis should include traits like:</p>
                        <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 1.8;">
                            <li>Resilience</li>
                            <li>Adherence</li>
                            <li>Kinesiophobia</li>
                            <li>Graded exposure needs</li>
                        </ul>
                        
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;">Sometimes people need exposure to tough things to build psychological resilience. Sometimes they need exercise to be flowing, melodic, relaxing because they're already in high stress mode.</p>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="warning-box">
                        <h4>⚠️ Common Challenge: Training Around an Injury</h4>
                        <p style="margin: 10px 0;"><strong>Problem:</strong> How do we keep training the athlete who can't tolerate closed-chain knee dominant exercises with high enough loads to be protective against further injury?</p>
                        
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>If we fail:</strong> Focusing JUST on low-level rehab leads to:</p>
                        <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px;">
                            <li>Local tissue deconditioning</li>
                            <li>Systemic deconditioning relative to peers</li>
                            <li>Higher risk of subsequent injury on RTS</li>
                            <li>Longer times in rehab</li>
                        </ul>
                        
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Solution:</strong> Find the most specific exercise on the spectrum that you can still train with relatively high external loads to maintain:</p>
                        <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px;">
                            <li>Training tolerance in local tissue</li>
                            <li>Total systemic training load response</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="success-box">
                        <p><strong>Remember:</strong> There are many ways to vary an exercise to suit the individual. There's no one right way to squat, deadlift, press, etc. Find solutions, not problems. Remove barriers by finding techniques that suit the patient in their context.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="module-card">
                    <h3>Rule 3: Know Your Patient's Personal Preferences</h3>
                    
                    <p style="font-size: 1.2em; font-style: italic; margin: 15px 0;">
                        "Saying exercise does or doesn't work is like saying food does or doesn't work."
                    </p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 10px;">Food only works if the person eats it. Exercise only works if the person actually does it.</p>
                    
                    <div style="background: #f1f8e9; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 20px 0; border: 3px solid #4caf50;">
                        <h4>Dr. Robert Sapolsky's 4-Point Checklist for Maximum Buy-In</h4>
                        
                        <div style="margin: 20px 0;">
                            <h5 style="color: #2e7d32;">1. Some Level of Control / Autonomy</h5>
                            <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 1.8;">
                                <li>Likes and dislikes</li>
                                <li>Ability to "feel" the movement</li>
                                <li>Tolerance levels</li>
                                <li>Exercises described and collaborated vs. dictated</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        
                        <div style="margin: 20px 0;">
                            <h5 style="color: #2e7d32;">2. A Sense of Belonging</h5>
                            <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 1.8;">
                                <li>Shared patient-centered journey</li>
                                <li>Not going it alone</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        
                        <div style="margin: 20px 0;">
                            <h5 style="color: #2e7d32;">3. Some Sense of Predictability</h5>
                            <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 1.8;">
                                <li>Rough prognosis</li>
                                <li>What if they do the intervention vs. don't</li>
                                <li>Acceptable pain levels</li>
                                <li>Barometers for improvement</li>
                                <li>Progressions and regressions</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        
                        <div style="margin: 20px 0;">
                            <h5 style="color: #2e7d32;">4. An Outlet from Life's Stress</h5>
                            <ul style="margin: 10px 0 0 20px; line-height: 1.8;">
                                <li>Program should fit into patient's life</li>
                                <li>Not add undue stress</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="info-box">
                    <h3>📝 The 3 Rules in Shorthand</h3>
                    <ol style="margin: 15px 0 0 20px; font-size: 1.1em; line-height: 2;">
                        <li><strong>Know the biological impacts</strong> of exercise and how the body adapts</li>
                        <li><strong>Know the goals</strong> of your patient and your exercise prescription</li>
                        <li><strong>Know the personal preferences</strong> of the person in front of you</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
                
                <div class="success-box">
                    <h3>🎓 The Bottom Line</h3>
                    <p style="font-size: 1.1em; line-height: 1.8;">
                        For physiotherapists working with active populations, knowledge of S&C principles and how they affect tissue rehabilitation allows for clear communication around goals, timelines, and expectations. Knowing how to program ensures you can perform your duty of functional capacity assessment and risk mitigation - leaving no room for doubt in your decision-making.
                    </p>
                </div>
                
                <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 30px;">
                    <button class="button" onclick="showSection('quiz')">Test Your Knowledge →</button>
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <!-- Quiz Section -->
            <section id="quiz" class="section">
                <h2>Test Your Knowledge</h2>
                
                <div class="quiz-container">
                    <h3 style="text-align: center; margin-bottom: 20px;">Complete Framework Knowledge Quiz</h3>
                    
                    <div class="quiz-question" id="q1">
                        <h4>Question 1: What are the two nested envelopes in the Envelope of Function model?</h4>
                        <div class="quiz-options">
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(1, 'a')">A) Acute and chronic envelopes</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(1, 'b')">B) Tissue and system envelopes</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(1, 'c')">C) Physical and mental envelopes</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(1, 'd')">D) Local and global envelopes</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="quiz-feedback" id="feedback1"></div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="quiz-question" id="q2">
                        <h4>Question 2: Which cueing strategy uses the longest ground contact time and lowest peak force?</h4>
                        <div class="quiz-options">
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(2, 'a')">A) ATTACK cues</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(2, 'b')">B) FEEL cues</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(2, 'c')">C) ABSORB cues</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(2, 'd')">D) EXPOSE cues</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="quiz-feedback" id="feedback2"></div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="quiz-question" id="q3">
                        <h4>Question 3: When both tissue and system envelopes are small, which approach is mandatory?</h4>
                        <div class="quiz-options">
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(3, 'a')">A) EXPOSE + ATTACK cues</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(3, 'b')">B) PROTECT + ABSORB cues</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(3, 'c')">C) VALIDATE + FEEL cues</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(3, 'd')">D) VIOLATE + FEEL cues</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="quiz-feedback" id="feedback3"></div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="quiz-question" id="q4">
                        <h4>Question 4: Which quadrant is appropriate for Type 2a patients (endurance copers)?</h4>
                        <div class="quiz-options">
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(4, 'a')">A) Protect + Validate</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(4, 'b')">B) Protect + Violate</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(4, 'c')">C) Expose + Validate</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(4, 'd')">D) Expose + Violate</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="quiz-feedback" id="feedback4"></div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="quiz-question" id="q5">
                        <h4>Question 5: What LSI percentage is required to exit Phase 3 (Mid Phase)?</h4>
                        <div class="quiz-options">
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(5, 'a')">A) >60% LSI</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(5, 'b')">B) >70% LSI</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(5, 'c')">C) >90% LSI</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(5, 'd')">D) >95% LSI</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="quiz-feedback" id="feedback5"></div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="quiz-question" id="q6">
                        <h4>Question 6: ATTACK cues ("attack and explode") produce which force profile?</h4>
                        <div class="quiz-options">
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(6, 'a')">A) High impulse, low peak force</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(6, 'b')">B) Low impulse, high peak force</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(6, 'c')">C) Moderate both</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(6, 'd')">D) High impulse, high peak force</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="quiz-feedback" id="feedback6"></div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="quiz-question" id="q7">
                        <h4>Question 7: What factors comprise the SYSTEM envelope?</h4>
                        <div class="quiz-options">
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(7, 'a')">A) Inflammation, healing stage, tissue conditioning</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(7, 'b')">B) Psychological stress, sleep quality, cognitive load, life circumstances</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(7, 'c')">C) Pain levels, ROM, strength deficits</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(7, 'd')">D) Age, gender, training history</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="quiz-feedback" id="feedback7"></div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="quiz-question" id="q8">
                        <h4>Question 8: Which mechanism of mechanotransduction is BEST to maximize when external load and ROM are limited post-operatively?</h4>
                        <div class="quiz-options">
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(8, 'a')">A) Mechanical tension</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(8, 'b')">B) Muscle damage</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(8, 'c')">C) Metabolic stress/accumulation</div>
                            <div class="quiz-option" onclick="selectAnswer(8, 'd')">D) None - rest the tissue</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="quiz-feedback" id="feedback8"></div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <button class="button" onclick="submitQuiz()" style="display: block; margin: 30px auto;">Submit Quiz</button>
                    
                    <div class="quiz-score" id="quizScore"></div>
                </div>
            </section>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <script>
        let currentSection = 'overview';
        let sectionsVisited = ['overview'];
        
        const quizAnswers = {
            1: 'b',
            2: 'c',
            3: 'b',
            4: 'b',
            5: 'b',
            6: 'b',
            7: 'b',
            8: 'c'
        };
        
        const quizExplanations = {
            1: 'The Envelope of Function model consists of nested TISSUE and SYSTEM envelopes. Both must be assessed to determine appropriate loading strategies.',
            2: 'ABSORB cues ("land soft and slow") create long contact times (500ms+), low peak forces, and high total impulse - perfect for tissue protection.',
            3: 'When both tissue and system envelopes are compromised, PROTECT + ABSORB is mandatory to minimize peak forces and respect both capacity limitations.',
            4: 'Type 2a patients (endurance copers) have real tissue irritability but "push through" beliefs, requiring PROTECT + VIOLATE to challenge their toughness mindset while enforcing tissue protection.',
            5: 'Phase 3 exit criteria requires >70% LSI on functional assessments with all previous outcomes stable or improving.',
            6: 'ATTACK cues produce short contact times (150ms), HIGH peak forces, and LOW total impulse - used for performance and return to sport when envelopes support it.',
            7: 'The SYSTEM envelope includes global capacity factors: psychological stress, sleep quality, cognitive load, and life circumstances - all factors that can limit tissue capacity even when tissue is healthy.',
            8: 'When mechanical tension and muscle damage mechanisms are limited post-operatively, maximize METABOLIC STRESS using lower load, decreased ROM, high TUT, and low inter-set recovery.'
        };
        
        const userAnswers = {};
        
        function showSection(sectionId) {
            document.getElementById(currentSection).classList.remove('active');
            document.querySelector(`[onclick="showSection('${currentSection}')"]`).classList.remove('active');
            
            document.getElementById(sectionId).classList.add('active');
            document.querySelector(`[onclick="showSection('${sectionId}')"]`).classList.add('active');
            
            if (!sectionsVisited.includes(sectionId)) {
                sectionsVisited.push(sectionId);
                updateProgress();
            }
            
            currentSection = sectionId;
            window.scrollTo({top: 0, behavior: 'smooth'});
        }
        
        function updateProgress() {
            const totalSections = 7;
            const progress = (sectionsVisited.length / totalSections) * 100;
            document.getElementById('progress').style.width = progress + '%';
        }
        
        // Force curve visualization
        const curveData = {
            absorb: {
                peak: 60,
                duration: 350,
                color: '#3b82f6',
                label: 'High Impulse, Low Peak',
                gct: '~500ms'
            },
            feel: {
                peak: 120,
                duration: 200,
                color: '#a855f7',
                label: 'Moderate Both',
                gct: '~300ms'
            },
            attack: {
                peak: 180,
                duration: 100,
                color: '#ec4899',
                label: 'High Peak, Low Impulse',
                gct: '~150ms'
            }
        };
        
        let currentCue = 'absorb';
        
        function selectCue(cue) {
            currentCue = cue;
            
            ['absorb', 'feel', 'attack'].forEach(c => {
                const btn = document.getElementById('btn-' + c);
                if (btn) {
                    if (c === cue) {
                        btn.className = 'cue-btn active';
                    } else {
                        btn.className = 'cue-btn';
                    }
                }
            });
            
            drawCurve(cue);
        }
        
        function drawCurve(cue) {
            const data = curveData[cue];
            const startX = 80;
            const endX = startX + data.duration;
            const baseY = 200;
            const peakY = baseY - data.peak;
            const midX = (startX + endX) / 2;
            
            const curvePath = `M ${startX} ${baseY} Q ${midX} ${peakY} ${endX} ${baseY}`;
            const pathEl = document.getElementById('curve-path');
            if (pathEl) {
                pathEl.setAttribute('d', curvePath);
                pathEl.setAttribute('stroke', data.color);
            }
            
            const fillPath = `${curvePath} L ${endX} ${baseY} L ${startX} ${baseY} Z`;
            const fillEl = document.getElementById('curve-fill');
            if (fillEl) {
                fillEl.setAttribute('d', fillPath);
                fillEl.setAttribute('fill', data.color);
            }
            
            const peakEl = document.getElementById('peak-marker');
            if (peakEl) {
                peakEl.setAttribute('cx', midX);
                peakEl.setAttribute('cy', peakY);
                peakEl.setAttribute('fill', data.color);
            }
            
            const labelEl = document.getElementById('curve-label');
            if (labelEl) {
                labelEl.textContent = data.label;
                labelEl.style.backgroundColor = data.color;
            }
            
            const gctEl = document.getElementById('gct-label');
            if (gctEl) {
                gctEl.textContent = 'Ground Contact Time: ' + data.gct;
            }
        }
        
        function selectAnswer(questionNum, answer) {
            const options = document.querySelectorAll(`#q${questionNum} .quiz-option`);
            options.forEach(opt => opt.classList.remove('selected'));
            
            event.target.classList.add('selected');
            userAnswers[questionNum] = answer;
        }
        
        function submitQuiz() {
            let score = 0;
            const totalQuestions = Object.keys(quizAnswers).length;
            
            if (Object.keys(userAnswers).length < totalQuestions) {
                alert('Please answer all questions before submitting!');
                return;
            }
            
            for (let q = 1; q <= totalQuestions; q++) {
                const correct = quizAnswers[q];
                const userAnswer = userAnswers[q];
                const feedback = document.getElementById(`feedback${q}`);
                const options = document.querySelectorAll(`#q${q} .quiz-option`);
                
                options.forEach(opt => {
                    const optionLetter = opt.textContent.charAt(0).toLowerCase();
                    if (optionLetter === correct) {
                        opt.classList.add('correct');
                    }
                    if (optionLetter === userAnswer && userAnswer !== correct) {
                        opt.classList.add('incorrect');
                    }
                });
                
                if (userAnswer === correct) {
                    score++;
                    feedback.className = 'quiz-feedback show correct';
                    feedback.innerHTML = `<strong>✅ Correct!</strong> ${quizExplanations[q]}`;
                } else {
                    feedback.className = 'quiz-feedback show incorrect';
                    feedback.innerHTML = `<strong>❌ Incorrect.</strong> ${quizExplanations[q]}`;
                }
            }
            
            const percentage = Math.round((score / totalQuestions) * 100);
            const scoreDiv = document.getElementById('quizScore');
            scoreDiv.className = 'quiz-score show';
            
            let message = '';
            let color = '';
            
            if (percentage >= 90) {
                message = '🎉 Outstanding! You have excellent mastery of the complete framework!';
                color = '#4caf50';
            } else if (percentage >= 70) {
                message = '👍 Great work! You have solid understanding of the core concepts.';
                color = '#2196f3';
            } else if (percentage >= 50) {
                message = '📚 Good effort! Review the material to strengthen your knowledge.';
                color = '#ff9800';
            } else {
                message = '💪 Keep studying! Review each section carefully.';
                color = '#f44336';
            }
            
            scoreDiv.innerHTML = `
                <h3 style="color: ${color};">Your Score: ${score}/${totalQuestions} (${percentage}%)</h3>
                <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin: 20px 0;">${message}</p>
                <button class="button" onclick="resetQuiz()">Retake Quiz</button>
            `;
            
            scoreDiv.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', block: 'nearest' });
        }
        
        function resetQuiz() {
            for (let key in userAnswers) {
                delete userAnswers[key];
            }
            
            for (let q = 1; q <= 8; q++) {
                const options = document.querySelectorAll(`#q${q} .quiz-option`);
                options.forEach(opt => {
                    opt.classList.remove('selected', 'correct', 'incorrect');
                });
                
                const feedback = document.getElementById(`feedback${q}`);
                feedback.className = 'quiz-feedback';
                feedback.innerHTML = '';
            }
            
            document.getElementById('quizScore').className = 'quiz-score';
            document.getElementById('q1').scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth' });
        }
        
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
            drawCurve('absorb');
        });
        
        updateProgress();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
